in a wild hurry to return books

00:44:11.950 --> 00:44:18.110
to the National Gallery of Art
Library, I read parts of a book

00:44:18.110 --> 00:44:21.400
on British art that
you're referring to.

00:44:21.400 --> 00:44:26.030
And indeed, there were
very strong feelings

00:44:26.030 --> 00:44:31.250
about not showing feeling
and especially in men.

00:44:31.250 --> 00:44:34.280
So, this is not unusual.

00:44:34.280 --> 00:44:39.430
It's the reasons for not
doing it differ, I suspect.

00:44:39.430 --> 00:44:42.380
I'm not familiar enough
with the European situation

00:44:42.380 --> 00:44:46.020
but I think the Chinese
situation is also very complex.

00:44:46.020 --> 00:44:50.280
And most people will argue it's
because of Confucian decorum.

00:44:50.280 --> 00:44:51.580
Smoothing the face.

00:44:51.580 --> 00:44:53.540
You know, you find these in text

00:44:53.540 --> 00:44:56.710
that date back to
the 6th century.

00:44:56.710 --> 00:45:00.130
But my question was, well,

00:45:00.130 --> 00:45:02.940
certainly surely things
[inaudible] change when you get

00:45:02.940 --> 00:45:04.540
into the 16th century
and that they were --

00:45:04.540 --> 00:45:06.820
it was more complex and there
were other issues involved.

00:45:06.820 --> 00:45:08.420
But you're absolutely right.

00:45:08.420 --> 00:45:13.980
The thing that really struck
me as being so different,

00:45:13.980 --> 00:45:15.620
though, was the La Brun.

00:45:15.620 --> 00:45:19.560
And his book -- or based on
a lecture about the passions

00:45:19.560 --> 00:45:22.030
that he gave to the
Academy in the 17th century

00:45:22.030 --> 00:45:23.830
where he was talking
about muscular, I mean,

00:45:23.830 --> 00:45:28.170
focused on muscular contractions
in every face that he described.

00:45:28.170 --> 00:45:30.810
And that is what's
missing -- or not missing.

00:45:30.810 --> 00:45:32.770
Is not relevant to
the Chinese case.

00:45:32.770 --> 00:45:34.930
Because of the completely
different notion

00:45:34.930 --> 00:45:39.620
of how a face moves
and how a body moves.

00:45:39.620 --> 00:45:42.220
But your point was
absolutely correct.

00:45:42.220 --> 00:45:44.210
Yes. Absolutely taken,
well taken.

00:45:44.210 --> 00:45:46.290
That class distinction
determines --

00:45:46.290 --> 00:45:48.970
will determine pictorial
representation of emotion.

00:45:54.890 --> 00:45:56.480
Any other questions?

00:45:56.480 --> 00:46:02.140
So, did convince you all that
Hongshou was incorporating --

00:46:02.140 --> 00:46:04.670
or appropriating
print convention?

00:46:04.670 --> 00:46:06.390
I'd really love to know
from you, other historians

00:46:06.390 --> 00:46:08.690
in the audience, actually.

00:46:11.780 --> 00:46:13.080
Oh, dear, I hope I did.

00:46:13.080 --> 00:46:14.880
[Laughs].

00:46:14.880 --> 00:46:22.210
[ Inaudible response ]

00:46:22.210 --> 00:46:26.210
I'm sorry, I didn't catch.

00:46:26.210 --> 00:46:27.510
[Inaudible response].

00:46:27.510 --> 00:46:32.590
Oh, this one of the
drunkard on the banana palms,

00:46:32.590 --> 00:46:36.470
which by the way, for decades
and decades was identified

00:46:36.470 --> 00:46:38.990
as a self-portrait of Hongshou.

00:46:38.990 --> 00:46:40.780
And I disagree entirely.

00:46:40.780 --> 00:46:44.200
And the Met has recently
overturned that --

00:46:44.200 --> 00:46:47.880
has removed that label from
[inaudible] from the leaf.

00:46:47.880 --> 00:46:50.940
This comes from the
Metropolitan.

00:46:50.940 --> 00:46:54.300
You can -- the Met
is very generous

00:46:54.300 --> 00:46:56.350
in their -- don't touch that.

00:46:56.350 --> 00:47:00.920
Very generous in their -- at
their site, their website.

00:47:00.920 --> 00:47:06.110
You just type in
Hongshou and you can get

00:47:06.110 --> 00:47:10.270
to this and download it.

00:47:10.270 --> 00:47:11.570
[Inaudible response].

00:47:11.570 --> 00:47:12.870
It's an album.

00:47:12.870 --> 00:47:15.000
It's an album.

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:16.300
So, like this.

00:47:16.300 --> 00:47:18.620
You -- yes.

00:47:18.620 --> 00:47:21.380
And it's -- this is
an interesting one

00:47:21.380 --> 00:47:25.680
in that it also has pictures,
paintings by his son.

00:47:25.680 --> 00:47:29.630
So, I think the album was put
together by somebody else.

00:47:29.630 --> 00:47:31.730
I don't think Chen
Hongshou put it together.

00:47:31.730 --> 00:47:34.620
Most people date it
to about the 1630s.

00:47:34.620 --> 00:47:40.230
But it was actually
assembled after that time.

00:47:40.230 --> 00:47:41.860
I'm sorry, I misunderstood
your question.

00:47:41.860 --> 00:47:43.660
Yes.

00:47:43.660 --> 00:48:02.960
[ Inaudible question ]

00:48:02.960 --> 00:48:06.430
Because, when gentleman were
not supposed to be shown

00:48:06.430 --> 00:48:08.040
with any kind of
distress or emotion.

00:48:08.040 --> 00:48:12.150
I mean, even if they were
worried -- you got that part.

00:48:12.150 --> 00:48:14.380
So, how did he reanimate this?

00:48:14.380 --> 00:48:15.890
How did he go about doing this?

00:48:15.890 --> 00:48:18.930
I'm arguing that it's because
-- he was a print designer.

00:48:18.930 --> 00:48:25.290
So, he did make illustrations
for printed books in the 1630s.

00:48:25.290 --> 00:48:26.850
And at first I thought, well,

00:48:26.850 --> 00:48:28.480
it must have come
from that experience.

00:48:28.480 --> 00:48:32.300
But this picture is often
dated prior to that time.

00:48:32.300 --> 00:48:35.670
So, I think he may have
been inspired by books

00:48:35.670 --> 00:48:37.280
with which he was familiar.

00:48:37.280 --> 00:48:39.310
Which often were illustrated.

00:48:39.310 --> 00:48:43.410
This was the prime time
for printed illustration.

00:48:43.410 --> 00:48:49.170
The -- no one else did it.

00:48:49.170 --> 00:48:51.250
Is what's so extraordinary
about Hongshou.

00:48:51.250 --> 00:48:55.080
And I think that -- you
know, he's -- I've said it.

00:48:55.080 --> 00:48:56.740
There's only one
sentence in which I --

00:48:56.740 --> 00:49:00.500
or phrase that I said he
was noted for being weird.

00:49:00.500 --> 00:49:04.890
His contemporaries said
he's strange and startling.

00:49:04.890 --> 00:49:07.090
There was one collector
who claimed that he had

00:49:07.090 --> 00:49:09.620
to put his paintings in a box
because he could only look

00:49:09.620 --> 00:49:10.920
at them for so much --

00:49:10.920 --> 00:49:13.240
for so long and he had
to keep them hidden.

00:49:13.240 --> 00:49:16.200
And there are many,
many commentators write

00:49:16.200 --> 00:49:18.590
about the oddity
of Chen Hongshou.

00:49:18.590 --> 00:49:21.830
In fact, most contemporary --
people who are writing today,

00:49:21.830 --> 00:49:23.660
will focus, he's weird.

00:49:23.660 --> 00:49:25.330
But I began to wonder, well,

00:49:25.330 --> 00:49:28.580
what exactly did they think
was weird about Chen Hongshou.

00:49:28.580 --> 00:49:30.870
I mean people in
the 17th century.

00:49:30.870 --> 00:49:34.840
And because not very many
art writers will say, well,

00:49:34.840 --> 00:49:36.540
it's because of this
or because of that.

00:49:36.540 --> 00:49:38.130
They'll just say, it's odd.

00:49:38.130 --> 00:49:40.500
Some -- there's one
person I know who wrote

00:49:40.500 --> 00:49:42.020
about the distortion of form.

00:49:42.020 --> 00:49:43.320
But they don't use that word.

00:49:43.320 --> 00:49:46.030
That is a word that
modern scholars use.

00:49:46.030 --> 00:49:48.380
So, my thought about
what was odd

00:49:48.380 --> 00:49:51.760
for contemporary viewers
was the juxtaposition

00:49:51.760 --> 00:49:53.710
of disparate genres.

00:49:53.710 --> 00:49:58.510
Print was not considered
as important as painting.

00:49:58.510 --> 00:50:05.390
I mean, it was a -- I was
questioned about this at CASVA.

00:50:05.390 --> 00:50:07.270
And it didn't really occur

00:50:07.270 --> 00:50:10.370
to me how really radically
different China is.

00:50:10.370 --> 00:50:13.860
I can count on one hand,
and I would be hard

00:50:13.860 --> 00:50:18.590
to finish my fingers, with
the number of painters

00:50:18.590 --> 00:50:20.800
who also were print makers.

00:50:20.800 --> 00:50:24.380
Now in the 17th century
in Europe, you know,

00:50:24.380 --> 00:50:25.680
hundreds and hundreds.

00:50:25.680 --> 00:50:32.550
Right? So, it's a totally
different engagement with print.

00:50:32.550 --> 00:50:36.030
Most of the print designers, we
don't even know who they are.

00:50:36.030 --> 00:50:37.330
We know the engravers.

00:50:37.330 --> 00:50:38.860
What's curious, we
know the block cutters.

00:50:38.860 --> 00:50:41.940
But we don't the people
who designed the pictures.

00:50:41.940 --> 00:50:44.150
Except in the case of
really famous painters

00:50:44.150 --> 00:50:45.860
such as Chen Hongshou,
[foreign name].

00:50:45.860 --> 00:50:47.840
But again, two, and then.

00:50:47.840 --> 00:50:49.140
Not too many.

00:50:49.140 --> 00:50:50.440
So, that's a really
major difference.

00:50:50.440 --> 00:50:54.740
So, incorporating print into
this very esteemed genre

00:50:54.740 --> 00:50:59.670
or painting or thing, painting,
was I'm beginning to think

00:50:59.670 --> 00:51:02.030
or that was my theory, anyway.

00:51:02.030 --> 00:51:05.660
It's what made him
weird to his audience.

00:51:05.660 --> 00:51:06.960
His first audience.

00:51:06.960 --> 00:51:09.170
Yes. It doesn't seem
so weird to us.

00:51:09.170 --> 00:51:10.530
But I think it may have been.

00:51:10.530 --> 00:51:15.730
And he's juxtaposing other very
incongruous manners of drawing

00:51:15.730 --> 00:51:17.030
in this particular picture.

00:51:17.030 --> 00:51:19.220
We get -- let's see
if I can go backward.

00:51:19.220 --> 00:51:24.020
I think I have the [inaudible].

00:51:24.020 --> 00:51:26.470
Somewhere back here.

00:51:26.470 --> 00:51:29.920
There. He -- sorry.

00:51:29.920 --> 00:51:33.660
He's trying to give
the sense of illusion.

00:51:33.660 --> 00:51:36.710
Of three-dimensionality
in the robe.

00:51:36.710 --> 00:51:40.430
With the stripes of the dark
gray, and then the white.

00:51:40.430 --> 00:51:44.430
Which was an antique
manner of drawing.

00:51:44.430 --> 00:51:46.980
How he came to know
about this, I don't know.

00:51:46.980 --> 00:51:50.850
Many people have argued that
he was looking at forgeries

00:51:50.850 --> 00:51:55.050
and the oddity of his
representation was

00:51:55.050 --> 00:51:57.300
because he was looking
at fake paintings

00:51:57.300 --> 00:52:00.120
that were popular at this time.

00:52:00.120 --> 00:52:03.030
But the flatness of the
face and those signs

00:52:03.030 --> 00:52:06.050
of sorrow are not
three -dimensional.

00:52:06.050 --> 00:52:07.500
So, you've got the
three-dimensional,

00:52:07.500 --> 00:52:08.800
you've got the flat.

00:52:08.800 --> 00:52:10.600
You've got different things

00:52:10.600 --> 00:52:12.650
that are clashing
against one another.

00:52:12.650 --> 00:52:15.440
So, it's not just the
print and the painting.

00:52:15.440 --> 00:52:19.890
It's other things, I think,
that are at work here, clashing.

00:52:19.890 --> 00:52:24.660
And that is what, I think,
was discomforting and unusual

00:52:24.660 --> 00:52:28.410
to his contemporaries, in my
opinion now, today, anyway.

00:52:28.410 --> 00:52:29.710
[Laughs]. Yes.

00:52:29.710 --> 00:52:35.290
&gt;&gt; I have a question
that -- about emotion.

00:52:35.290 --> 00:52:36.770
[inaudible] for the --
language of [inaudible].

00:52:36.770 --> 00:52:43.770
Looking at the fine
lines of Chen Hongshou,

00:52:43.770 --> 00:52:46.460
he was a great artist
[inaudible] craft.

00:52:46.460 --> 00:52:51.490
I was thinking about
his contemporaries,

00:52:51.490 --> 00:52:53.810
[inaudible] who expressed
his emotions

00:52:53.810 --> 00:52:57.760
through the brushstrokes.

00:52:57.760 --> 00:53:01.410
Do you consider including,
in your [inaudible] emotions

00:53:01.410 --> 00:53:08.870
in Chinese paintings emoted
through the brush language --

00:53:08.870 --> 00:53:10.940
&gt;&gt; Anne Burkus-Chasson: Through
the body or gesture, you mean?

00:53:10.940 --> 00:53:13.110
Or actually the stroke, itself?

00:53:13.110 --> 00:53:14.410
&gt;&gt; The strokes.

00:53:14.410 --> 00:53:21.200
Because two ways of painting
the [inaudible] the psychology

00:53:21.200 --> 00:53:23.910
of artist.

00:53:23.910 --> 00:53:33.000
Maybe it's fair to say the
same about [inaudible].

00:53:33.000 --> 00:53:36.900
Brushstrokes are very
nervous, direct --

00:53:36.900 --> 00:53:40.070
&gt;&gt; Anne Burkus-Chasson: Mm-hmm.

00:53:40.070 --> 00:53:46.610
Indeed. I have not -- this
is a work in progress.

00:53:46.610 --> 00:53:51.430
And this is actually just very
recent work that I've done.

00:53:51.430 --> 00:53:53.920
So, no, I can't say that
I've gone in that direction

00:53:53.920 --> 00:53:58.780
but thank you for reminding
me though, of the more --

00:53:58.780 --> 00:54:02.460
Chen Hongshou is extremely
restrained as you point out.

00:54:02.460 --> 00:54:06.910
Even when he's working
with dry ink on paper.

00:54:06.910 --> 00:54:09.290
It's still restrained
and very quiet

00:54:09.290 --> 00:54:13.040
in the way he uses his brush.

00:54:13.040 --> 00:54:14.900
And extremely disciplined.

00:54:14.900 --> 00:54:16.200
Tight and controlled.

00:54:16.200 --> 00:54:19.360
Whereas [inaudible] is a
different kind of control

00:54:19.360 --> 00:54:21.660
but nonetheless, it's --

00:54:21.660 --> 00:54:25.000
one seems to respond
kinesthetically, I think.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:27.530
Is that what you're
kind of getting at?

00:54:27.530 --> 00:54:29.220
No, I have not explored that.

00:54:29.220 --> 00:54:31.120
But that would certainly
be worth exploring.

00:54:31.120 --> 00:54:34.600
Indeed, as another form of
emotion in Chinese painting.

00:54:34.600 --> 00:54:38.620
Which I confess, I -- my
husband is a Europeanist

00:54:38.620 --> 00:54:42.020
and I often tease him
about one thing or another.

00:54:42.020 --> 00:54:46.150
Of course, assuming the
Chinese art is superior.

00:54:46.150 --> 00:54:49.370
But I had to confess, I
had not really admitted

00:54:49.370 --> 00:54:53.220
to myself how subtle
these signs of emotion are

00:54:53.220 --> 00:54:55.720
in Chinese figure painting.

00:54:55.720 --> 00:55:01.750
So, this was actually revelatory
to me, to do this work

00:55:01.750 --> 00:55:05.020
and to look so closely
at this things.

00:55:05.020 --> 00:55:09.850
I mean just the little eyes
going -- and that's it.

00:55:09.850 --> 00:55:12.770
You know. So, that's why
I was really interested

00:55:12.770 --> 00:55:14.070
in the [foreign language] works.

00:55:14.070 --> 00:55:19.030
[Foreign language] work on the
musculature and medical theory.

00:55:19.030 --> 00:55:21.750
Found really useful for that.

00:55:21.750 --> 00:55:25.220
Anyway, that's going off your
subject of [foreign language].

00:55:25.220 --> 00:55:32.040
&gt;&gt; I'm going to look over to
the subject to the spirit of --

00:55:32.040 --> 00:55:35.950
to the areas of the theater.

00:55:35.950 --> 00:55:38.250
&gt;&gt; Anne Burkus-Chasson:
Indeed, yes.

00:55:41.770 --> 00:55:43.470
That's a huge question.

00:55:43.470 --> 00:55:47.150
For those of you
who are unfamiliar.

00:55:47.150 --> 00:55:52.020
There's been quite a bit
of work on the relationship

00:55:52.020 --> 00:55:55.250
between printed illustration
and the theater.

00:55:55.250 --> 00:56:02.270
And a number of scholars,
both Chinese and also people

00:56:02.270 --> 00:56:08.460
who are trained in this country
have argued that the drama

00:56:08.460 --> 00:56:10.700
of printed illustration came

00:56:10.700 --> 00:56:15.500
from the print designers
seeing plays.

00:56:15.500 --> 00:56:18.030
And that it was a
memetic exchange.

00:56:18.030 --> 00:56:22.090
So, that they copied the
gestures that they saw in a play

00:56:22.090 --> 00:56:24.130
and put it in their
illustrations.

00:56:24.130 --> 00:56:27.720
I personally have generally
been opposed to that.

00:56:27.720 --> 00:56:33.440
I can't see a designer
needing to go to a play

00:56:33.440 --> 00:56:35.230
to actually -- and to copy it.

00:56:35.230 --> 00:56:37.240
I mean, I know that
there are copies.

00:56:37.240 --> 00:56:39.650
There actually are
representations of plays

00:56:39.650 --> 00:56:42.010
in the prints and
they don't really look

00:56:42.010 --> 00:56:44.840
like the emotional pict --

00:56:44.840 --> 00:56:47.080
so, I think there's
actually a distinction

00:56:47.080 --> 00:56:51.180
between the way a play is
represented in a print.

00:56:51.180 --> 00:56:54.460
And then the way emotion
is represented in a print.

00:56:54.460 --> 00:56:58.820
And so, I'm not -- I think it's
much more indebted to painting.

00:56:58.820 --> 00:57:00.120
Conventions of painting rather

00:57:00.120 --> 00:57:03.530
than to opera, operatic
gestures.

00:57:03.530 --> 00:57:06.740
We also don't know very
much about the gestures.

00:57:06.740 --> 00:57:11.020
And nonetheless, someone
at CASVA reminded me

00:57:11.020 --> 00:57:14.890
of Bassano [phonetic
spelling] painting experience

00:57:14.890 --> 00:57:16.970
in 15th century Italy?

00:57:16.970 --> 00:57:18.270
Right? Okay.

00:57:18.270 --> 00:57:22.150
And he was interested in
gesture as well in that book.

00:57:22.150 --> 00:57:23.890
Not a large part of it.

00:57:23.890 --> 00:57:26.090
But there is a small
part of it on gesture.

00:57:26.090 --> 00:57:29.150
Where he emphasized that we need

00:57:29.150 --> 00:57:30.490
to know what these
gestures mean.

00:57:30.490 --> 00:57:32.200
So, how do we find out?

00:57:32.200 --> 00:57:35.090
And he went to --
instead of suggesting this

00:57:35.090 --> 00:57:37.620
from a memetic relationship,
with drama,

00:57:37.620 --> 00:57:41.440
he went to -- where did he go?

00:57:41.440 --> 00:57:44.950
Now it's slipping my brain.

00:57:48.050 --> 00:57:49.470
He -- oh, I know.

00:57:49.470 --> 00:57:53.980
He -- when monks had to
take vows of silence,

00:57:53.980 --> 00:57:55.280
what were their hand gestures?

00:57:55.280 --> 00:58:00.770
And so he found text that
described the gestures of monks.

00:58:00.770 --> 00:58:05.210
That's another -- that's one of
my things on my to-do list here.

00:58:05.210 --> 00:58:09.020
because I think that kind
of approach might be --

00:58:09.020 --> 00:58:13.810
would suit my intellectual
inclinations more than the idea

00:58:13.810 --> 00:58:17.050
of copying the way a gesture
was performed on stage.

00:58:17.050 --> 00:58:20.700
But there is no question on
the other hand, I don't think

00:58:20.700 --> 00:58:26.370
that this gesture of the hand
to the face, meant sorrow.

00:58:26.370 --> 00:58:31.270
And it could be that there
was just general knowledge,

00:58:31.270 --> 00:58:35.890
as Bassano would say --
I'm causing trouble here.

00:58:35.890 --> 00:58:39.440
General knowledge that
this gesture meant sorrow.

00:58:39.440 --> 00:58:43.290
So, I'm still working
on that issue.

00:58:43.290 --> 00:58:45.600
But it's a very important
one, I think, actually.

00:58:45.600 --> 00:58:47.930
His opera was so important
during that period.

00:58:47.930 --> 00:58:53.050
&gt;&gt; You just mentioned
that you seem

00:58:53.050 --> 00:58:56.970
to prefer the Chinese painting

00:58:56.970 --> 00:58:59.720
because the [inaudible] you
think is a little bit superior

00:58:59.720 --> 00:59:01.020
in your opinion?

00:59:01.020 --> 00:59:02.320
I understand that --

00:59:02.320 --> 00:59:03.620
&gt;&gt; Anne Burkus-Chasson:
Oh, I just tease --

00:59:03.620 --> 00:59:05.820
this is a source of
teasing for my husband.

00:59:05.820 --> 00:59:11.030
I shouldn't even have
mentioned something so bold.

00:59:11.030 --> 00:59:15.240
But it's true.

00:59:15.240 --> 00:59:16.540
[Laughing, inaudible response].

00:59:16.540 --> 00:59:17.840
Sorry. Would you
repeat your question?

00:59:17.840 --> 00:59:19.140
I was overwhelmed with
feeling embarrassed.

00:59:19.140 --> 00:59:21.770
&gt;&gt; You just mentioned

00:59:21.770 --> 00:59:23.210
that something is more
superior in your mind.

00:59:23.210 --> 00:59:26.960
Could you elaborate that?

00:59:26.960 --> 00:59:28.260
Because --

00:59:28.260 --> 00:59:29.560
&gt;&gt; Anne Burkus-Chasson: You
know, to tell you the truth I --

00:59:29.560 --> 00:59:31.690
the time I've spent at CASVA
I have a new appreciation

00:59:31.690 --> 00:59:32.990
of even Italian art.

00:59:32.990 --> 00:59:35.320
And I have never
loved Italian art.

00:59:35.320 --> 00:59:38.230
And you have to love
Italian art at CASVA.

00:59:38.230 --> 00:59:40.770
And another thing that I
must say, I was really moved

00:59:40.770 --> 00:59:45.480
by the Bellini and the
Piata, and the words that --

00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:47.940
those swelling eyes
will bring groans.

00:59:47.940 --> 00:59:51.160
And there is something that is
so moving, so very beautiful.

00:59:51.160 --> 00:59:54.070
So, I confess -- I
confess this to my husband.

00:59:54.070 --> 00:59:57.030
I was simply ignorant.

00:59:57.030 --> 00:59:58.410
There you have it.

00:59:58.410 --> 01:00:00.080
They're just really,
really different.

01:00:00.080 --> 01:00:04.170
And that's where I
guess my interest

01:00:04.170 --> 01:00:07.800
in drawing contrast now,
which I was frankly,

01:00:07.800 --> 01:00:09.160
never interested in doing.

01:00:09.160 --> 01:00:13.540
Is to highlight how really
different the Chinese situation

01:00:13.540 --> 01:00:14.900
is or case.

01:00:14.900 --> 01:00:20.260
I don't -- I'm less interested
in comparative studies that try

01:00:20.260 --> 01:00:24.710
to -- well, most recently a
book on [foreign language]

01:00:24.710 --> 01:00:26.960
in the same book with
[foreign language].

01:00:26.960 --> 01:00:31.480
It's a brilliant book
and beautifully written.

01:00:31.480 --> 01:00:35.400
But, you know, I question is
she trying to go too far to try

01:00:35.400 --> 01:00:39.610
to create this early modern
spirit in China and Europe.

01:00:39.610 --> 01:00:43.420
I'm not entirely
convinced by that.

01:00:43.420 --> 01:00:48.090
But the -- I take
back everything I said

01:00:48.090 --> 01:00:49.400
about [laughs].

01:00:49.400 --> 01:00:53.310
Actually, I love
European art a lot.

01:00:53.310 --> 01:00:57.910
There were just certain
periods that I was biased about.

01:00:57.910 --> 01:01:00.090
No more.

01:01:00.090 --> 01:01:01.390
